===Alternative forms=== 
* {{l|oko|言利}} {{q|logographic variant}}
* {{l|oko|曰利}} {{q|logographic variant}}

===Pronunciation===
The final phonogram of the logographic variants shows that the verb stem has a final *-i or *-y, while the entirely phonogramic form {{l|oko|乃}} shows that the phonology of the word is overall similar to Middle Chinese */nʌi/. Thus it is believed to be the ancestor of the Middle and Modern Korean [[cranberry morpheme]] {{ko-inline|뇌|tr=nwoy}}, used in some verb stems relating to speech, and is reconstructed as *nwoy.

===Verb===
{{head|oko|verb|tr=*nwoy-}}

# to [[speak]]; to [[say]]

====Descendants====
* {{desc|ko|되뇌다|t=to repeat the same thing|der=1}}
* {{desc|ko|뇌까리다|t=to say whatever comes to mind|der=1}}

===Notes===
This term is given as a native Korean equivalent of the Chinese verb {{m|zh|言}} in Korean-language interpretive ''{{w|gugyeol}}'' glosses to the Buddhist canon, made between the tenth and thirteenth centuries. Interpretive ''gugyeol'' encodes guidelines by which a Korean speaker could have read out a Classical Chinese text in its native Korean translation, much like Japanese {{w|kanbun}}. These glosses accordingly instruct the Korean reader to read out the Chinese verb "to speak" as {{m|oko|乃}}, allowing us to understand the meaning of *nwoy.

It is not attested outside compounds in Middle Korean sources.

